description_text:
 Description 

 The Sippy Web Phone is an innovative product that allows anyone to add phone capabilities to their web applications. Unlike traditional softphone solutions, it is browser- and platform-independent, does not require installation, and leaves no personal information on a computer after use. For more information see also http://www.sippysoft.com/products/web_phone/. 

 General Information 

 The Sippy Web Phone core is an java-applet. The applet is embedded into HTML page. When the applet works and an event on SIP side occurs, this event is passed into user browser via java-scripts functions. From other side, user can initiate an event for applet calling appropriate API function. 

 Embedding the applet into HTML code 

 The applet requires Java Runtime Environment at least version 1.5 to be installed on user side. Bellow is a sample HTML code to embed the applet:   



 <object name="webphone"
    classid="clsid:8AD9C840-044E-11D1-B3E9-00805F499D93"
    codebase="https://java.sun.com/update/1.6.0/jinstall-6-windows-i586.cab#Version=6,0,0,0"
    width="1" height="1">
    <param name="java_version" value="1.5+">
    <param name="code" value="com.doddlephone.sip.WebSipPhone.class" />
    <param name="codebase" value="/" />
    <param name="archive" value="webphone.jar" />
    <param name="mayscript" value="true" />
    <param name="cprt" value="Sippy Software, Inc" />
    <comment>   <!-- Non-WinIE Browsers -->
        <embed name="webphone"
            classid="java:com.doddlephone.sip.WebSipPhone.class"
            type="application/x-java-applet" width="1" height="1"
            pluginspage="http://java.sun.com/update/1.6.0/jre-6-windows-i586.xpi"
            java_version="1.5+"
            code="com.doddlephone.sip.WebSipPhone.class"
            codebase="/"
            archive="webphone.jar"
            mayscript="true"
            cprt="Sippy Software, Inc">
        </embed>
    </comment>
</object> 

 Note: The applet archive name in this example is webphone.jar and the file is located in the root directory of web server.



 API calls 

 Login(string userName, string authUserName, string password, string sipServer, string outboundProxy, string sipRealm, bool useHA1) 
 Register applet to the SIP server. 
 Parameters 


userName - username, string. 

authUserName - username for authentication purposes, string. 

password - password, string. 

sipServer - IP-address or hostname of SIP server, string. 

outboundProxy - IP-address or hostname of outbound proxy, string. If not used set it to null. 

sipRealm - SIP realm, string. 

useHA1 - if set to true the password field contains HA1-encoded password digest instead of actual password. 

 Bellow is an example in java-script: 



 var loSipProxy = 'demo.sippysoft.com';
var loSipRealm = 'sippysoft.com';
var loMyUserName  = '12345654321';
var loMyPassword  = 'mysecretpassord';
var loha1 = '6d41b3252e961e9dfaea26050dccb32a';

function Login() {
  if (!allowLogin){
    DisplayMessage('WebPhone is loading, please wait...', 2);
    return;
  }

  DisplayMessage('Trying to login...', 1);
  var applet = (document.webphone.length) ? document.webphone[1] : document.webphone;
  applet.Login(loMyUserName, loMyUserName, loha1, loSipProxy, null, loSipRealm, true);
} 


 eventHandler(msg) This call is used to handle general events generated by applet. Every time when the event occurs the applet calls this Java-Script function on the user browser side.


 Parameters 


msg - an event identifier, integer. Possible values:


 // as defined in the applet
var LS_REGISTERED      = 21000;
var LS_REGISTER_FAILED = 24000;
var LS_REGISTER_FAILED_NOT_CONNECT = LS_REGISTER_FAILED + 1;
var LS_REGISTER_FAILED_NOT_AUTHORIZED  = LS_REGISTER_FAILED + 2;
var LS_REGISTER_FAILED_TIMEOUT = LS_REGISTER_FAILED + 3;
var CS_REMOTE_ALERTING = 3000;
var CS_CONNECTED       = 4000;
var CS_DISCONNECTED    = 8000;
var CS_ALERTING        = 10000;
var CS_CAUSE_NORMAL    = 1;
var CS_CAUSE_BUSY      = 8;
var CS_CAUSE_CODEC_FAILURE = 21;
var APP_LOADED         = 1010; 





 Bellow is an example in java-script: 


 function eventHandler(msg) {

  switch (parseInt(msg)) {

    case APP_LOADED:
      allowLogin = 1;
      Login();

      break;

    case LS_REGISTERED:
      if (!isLogged)
        DisplayMessage('Login OK', 0);
      isLogged = 1;

      break;

    case CS_ALERTING:
      incomingCall = 1;

      break;
  }
} 


 Call(number)   

 Initiate a call. 

 Parameters 


number - phone number in form SipWebPhone <sip:# (without > at the end), string. 


 An example in java-script: 



 var exten = '22334455';
var applet = (document.webphone.length) ? document.webphone[1] : document.webphone;
applet.Call('SipWebPhone <sip:' + exten); 


 Hangup()   
 Hang up a call. 



 Parameters 

      No parameters.


 Accept() 

 Answer an incoming call.   

 Parameters 
      No parameters.


 contactIDHandler(number) 

 This call is called by the applet to provide an info about incoming number. 

 Parameters 


number - phone number of incoming call, string. 

 An example in java-script: 


 function contactIDHandler(number) {
  if (incomingCall) {
    var answer = confirm('Incoming call from ' + number + ', do you want to answer?');

    if (answer) {
      Accept();
    } else {
      incomingCall = 0;
      Hangup();
    }
  }
} 




 sendDTMF(n) 

 Send a DTMF digit. 

 Parameters 


n - DTMF digit, string. Possible values are from range 0-9,#,*. 

 An example in java-script: 


 function sendDTMF(n) {
  var applet = (document.webphone.length) ? document.webphone[1] : document.webphone;
  applet.SendDTMF(n);
} 




 Mute() 

 Mute audio 

 An example in java-script: 


 function Mute() {
  var applet = (document.webphone.length) ? document.webphone[1]:document.webphone;
  applet.Mute();
} 


 UnMute() 

 Unmute previously muted audio 


 function UnMute() {
 var applet = (document.webphone.length) ? document.webphone[1]:document.webphone;
 applet.UnMute();
} 


